<br>
Secondly any charm that can charm a mob hitting for 400+ and be used to help gain exp is a bit absurd imo.  <br>
<br>
I don't care if its mages, BLs, or warriors that get it.  Its absurd.<br>
<br>
For those enchanters posting here saying that CoD isn't all that...obviously it must be for most that have it because they use it and gain a lot of EXP.<br>
<br>
So you take a death and no rez and lose some exp.  Well that exp is going to be gained back pretty quickly soloing things right?  So I don't think that death is a valid arguement to 'oh, CoD has risks!!!'<br>
<br>
Funny that you don't see many chanters successfully charming and soling for EXP until 60+ (I'm talkin as a new char, not a twink with 255 int and 200 cha).  Why not?  Because charm breaks pretty often at lower levels and then you will probably die well over 80% of the time with 2 mobs beating on you.  <br>
<br>
The same risk applies with CoD but I don't think we need to go into great detail on the spell choice differences between a lvl 45 and a lvl 65 enchanter.<br>
<br>
However the thing is EXP gained.  So what if you lose 3, 4 blue.  You can make it all back with very minimal time.  At lvl 45 try eating 3 or 4 blue and then going back out trying to solo again.  You'll find yourself going backwards at a quick pace.  Losing 3 or 4 blue at 45 hurts anyone, solo or not.  The EXP gained at these levels just isn't all that great.<br>
<br>
Death is a pitiful excuse as a 'risk' in PoP.  The EXP is too high to say 'Oh I won't use this spell because there's a chance that after I make half a AA point of EXP, I might die!'.  Who cares if you die?  Eat the EXP loss, grind for an hour (being generous =P) and then you're back at where you started if not more.<br>
<br>
I'd say make CoD completely random and can break at any time, regardless of skill.  Still very powerful but now you take the chance at dying a lot more unless you're very good.<br>
<br>
By making it random, it becomes much harder to control but the really good chanters should still be ok if they play smart.<br>
<br>
Or have a few 'token' mobs around that can be charmed that do maybe 150 max dmg and have about same hps as mage pets.  That way they can be used for raid-type mobs for some extra damage but won't be able to be used to farm EXP at an extremely high rate. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wrathen@themagicianstower>Wrathen</A> at: 12/20/02 5:21:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wezloc>Wezloc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 57<br> <font color=#333333>(12/20/02 8:08:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=399.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: re:CoD</span><hr size=1> When a enchanter with the help of a cleric can charm a pet and haste it to do more damage then 3 or 4 roges something is wrong.  Enchanters gaining 1aa per 20mins isn't right, and I can't believe people are even arguing against it. That is completely broken and needs to be nerfed. I don't care what class it is, and if our crappy charm is overpowered nerf it too, not like I wanted it anyway. The best utility class in the game should not be able to out damage the best damage dealers in the game x 3.<br>
