<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=413004" target="top">Borstal</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thedwellerindarkness@themagicianstower>thedwellerindarkness</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 395<br> <font color=#333333>(12/20/02 11:57:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=399.topic&index=68>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are we to do about Command of Druzzil</span><hr size=1> I see many enchanters who say that charm is balanced because of the risks. Can anyone explain in what way the risks involved are any worse than the risks that solo mages face? Sure, we mages can't solo in the new planes, but if we could, in what way is a broken charm worse than a simple add that we might see? In fact given the huge variety of tools to deal with the situation that enchanters have, I'd say that enchanters have less risk involved than a mage.<br>
<br>
Broken charm means dealing with a mob that may hit for 500? That's not a danger of charming, that's a danger of soloing.<br>
<br>
I don't want to see charm taken away, but it should be tuned down some. A long recast on charms might be appropriate. A charm limit per mob might be appropriate (can't be charmed more than once per half hour?). The continual use of mana like bard charm isn't a bad idea. Charm should be a great way to turn an add into an ally, but not a mainstay tactic of a class, unless it was thier sole gig.<br>
<br>
If chanters can do that kind of damage as a primarily support role, how much damage should offensive melee and casters be doing? or how much utility should damage classes be given to help even out the roles? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fassade>Fassade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#333333>(12/21/02 1:44:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=399.topic&index=69>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are we to do about Command of Druzzil</span><hr size=1> [quote]Funny that you don't see many chanters successfully charming and soling for EXP until 60+ (I'm talkin as a new char, not a twink with 255 int and 200 cha). Why not? Because charm breaks pretty often at lower levels and then you will probably die well over 80% of the time with 2 mobs beating on you. [/quote]<br>
<br>
Charm breaks no more often or more quickly with Beguile than it does the higher level spells, and the death ratios are roughly equivalent, as well.  Enchanters have always charmed -- I have aggressively charmed, solo and in groups since level 20 and my second color stun.  (I was and am not a twink - I am only partially ashamed to admit I wore 3 pieces of cloth until level 46.)   Smart enchanters would pick the proper mobs to charm, and use whatever tools they could (speed, distance, runes, berserker, root, mez) to minimze the risk, but it was always there.<br>
<br>
The equation has always been the same -- buy yourself enough time to regain control, or die.  Without a dedicated healer, it is in fact more difficult to recharm a CoD pet than it was a Rockfiend in the Grey, a Guard in Kael, a Frog in OS, a Spectre in Oasis.  (Not being one the 200AA enchanters myself, I cannot vouch as to how easy or difficult they have it in PoP -- there are not many of those around.)  With a dedicated healer and an alert group, the enchanter has always been able to add significant damage with relatively low risk, as long as the group paid attention.  If the group slacked, they died.  CoD level mobs are at least as risky as the corresponding mobs were to corresponding enchanters from earlier eras.  This begs the question -- why does charm seem so much more popular now, even among enchanters who rarely used it?<br>
<br>
In my opinion, the answer is not that CoD is suddenly so much easier, it is that the downsides of death are not nearly as severe as they were in earlier eras.  There are two reasons for this:<br>
<br>
1) PoP experience yeilds.<br>
2) Graveyards.<br>
<br>
In earlier eras, if you charmed and hasted an Illis Knight in lower OS or a Fire Giant in SolB, you could outdamage a group, but, if you wiped your group, you were in for some pain.  As a result, people did not often do it.  (Yes, some still did, but pickup groups were far less tolerant.)  In PoP, the pain is almost nonexistent.  Did a charmed Hobgoblin wipe you deep in the Tunnels?  No problem -- CR is a 15-30 minute proposition, with all equipment, guaranteed.  Did you die three times in a row in PoV?  No problem -- 25 minutes of grinding will return ALL the experience lost, and then some.  <br>
<br>
PoP therefore encourages high-risk play, and it does not come higher than charm.  The risk of death is the same as it ever was for charm enchanters -- high, but manageable under certain circumstances with the proper backup -- but the penalties for failure are so mild that enchanters and groups are getting bolder in using the ability.  As groups become bolder about using charm, as the initial poster indicated, some have built groups around it to reduce the risk further.<br>
<br>
As long as the penalties for failure in PoP remain so minimal, people will keep angling for the highest reward behavior they can find, regardless of risk, and that is likely to remain charm, unless the skill is nerfed to near uselessness. <p>&lt;font size=&quot;-1&quot; face=&quot;Arial,Hevetica,Sans-Serif&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52833&quot;&gt;My Magelo Profile&lt;/a&gt; |<br>
