oh and:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for having 2 clerics in a group, I think a lot of clerics would say that is great. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You dont understand how the game works do you? <br>
Theres a reason there are so many damage classes and so few healing-capable classes. That is because there is supposed to be roughly a 1:3 ratio for healing:offense in most groups. <br>
<br>
Almost all full groups have this make up, even ae groups:<br>
1 class whos primary job is to heal<br>
2 classes who primary job is to mitigate damage<br>
3 classes whos primary job is to deal damage.<br>
<br>
The most common set up is 1 healer (cleric or druid usually), 1 tank (pal/shd/war), 1 slower (ench/sham/bard), and 3 damage dealers (mag/rog/wiz/nec/rang/bst)<br>
<br>
Some classes are less specilized, and have distinguished secondary roles. They can be paired up with other less specilized classes to reinforce these secondary roles to make them as strong as a specilized classes primary role. For example a good shaman and druid together through slowing and kiting/root parking, and hots and quick heals can simulate the healing of a cleric and the damage mitigation of an enchanter (both respective specialists in their fields).<br>
<br>
You see if groups take as many enchanters as they can get and 2 clerics, not only are you trivializing the game through broken experience making, but you are making it harder for <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>me, and players of other classes like mine</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to get exp. The pathetic 100-160 dps that offensive classes do is absolutely pointless when for a nominal risk an enchanter can do well over 160 (plus perform the real role the enchanter was designed to do primarily: damage mitigation)<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> As you stated, it's hard for a cleric to get a group if all clerics already have one.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
