<br>
- mages who agree with my proposition (of charm being out of line) being labeled as nerf beggers from enchanters trying to shift focus from the facts...<br>
<br>
- newbie mages and players who dont understand the game very well, saying that the dps &quot;is balanced because of the risk&quot; (as they do not understand how little risk it actually is, and really cant unless they understand a 60+ enchanters spells and tactics, and 60+ experience getting and zones in general)...<br>
<br>
My reactions are far from knee jerk tain, ive seen cod and understand its power well. I say your reaction is knee jerk, as you are basing your beliefs on your personal feelings that speaking negatively of other classes abilities is pety, not on the facts of the situation. My beliefs are based on facts i observe practically every time i exp.<br>
<br>
Heres an example of just how crazy cod is. I got into a pickup group today, we werent perfect really but we were ok. It was comprised of a cleric, shaman, paladin, ranger, myself, and a druid. We were in bot, trying to kill a named lightning giants. We did not have clarity or tash, so when we finally got to him we failed. This was because of the fact we could not stick malosinia or magic based slow, due to lack of advanced debuffing (tash, ect). Since it was not slowed well nor did we have clarity our cleric ran oom (btw, both enchanter abilities).<br>
As we wiped, an enchanter with cod and a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>dual boxed</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> cleric (which is more out of convienance and saftey than necessity) ran over there and soloed him with ease. Ill give you 1 guess how he did it, and what tool he used.<br>
<br>
So basically, what a full group of reasonably intelligent players has difficulty doing, an enchanter with a dual boxed cleric can. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>How much more obvious does it have to be</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->?<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Oh, and, Interesting that enchanters are supposed to do paladin damage. Could we get a link to where that is stated? or is that text lost with the one that says mages aren't damage dealers either?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Come on tain. You know what i meant by that statement. I meant that enchanters are the paladins of casters, meaning they are supposed to be mostly support/defense and light offense. If we dont agree on this point, why bother talking further?  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=noonievioletskies>NoonieVioletskies</A> at: 12/21/02 5:09:59 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2492<br> <font color=#333333>(12/21/02 6:08:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=399.topic&index=78>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are we to do about Command of Druzzil</span><hr size=1> One idea it occurs to me to explore is this.  Originally, summoned pets acted as NPCs, and this was changed because the rules favor NPCs too much.  Now summoned pets arc more like a hybrid of PC and NPC.<br>
<br>
That seems to be the root of the problem with charm.  The charmed mob, being a powerful NPC is just too powerful.<br>
<br>
Maybe charmed NPCs can lose some of the advantages of their NPCness, and be more comparable to PCs.  Alternately, special rules could apply to charmed pets.<br>
<br>
The risk or cost associated with charm does not appear balanced.  If all that is required to sustain a charmed mob is one priest, and the charmed mob outdamages multiple PC damage dealers <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(who require their own support)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then how can you avoid the conclusion that it is unbalanced?<br>
<br>
I want to see more concrete data on the benefits, costs and risks of charmed pets.<br>
<br>
